Now let me also check how the `model_lifecycle_key` works for matching ModelCallStarted with ModelCallCompleted. Looking at the function:

```rust
fn model_lifecycle_key(event: &Value) -> String {
    event_string(event, "run_id")
        .filter(|run_id| !run_id.is_empty())
        .or_else(|| event_string(event, "event_id"))
        .unwrap_or("-")
        .to_string()
}
```

This matches by run_id (if non-empty) or event_id. So ModelCallStarted and ModelCallCompleted in the same run_id will be paired by run_id.

Wait, that doesn't seem right. The pairing should be by model_call_id or something. Let me re-read... yes, it uses run_id as the key. This means within a run, ModelCallStarted and ModelCallCompleted are matched by run_id. But that means if a run has multiple model calls, only the first start and first completion will pair up.

Actually, looking at the code more carefully: the key is run_id. `open_model_calls.insert(key, ...)` - since it's a BTreeMap, inserting with the same key will overwrite the previous entry. So if you have two ModelCallStarted events with the same run_id, only the last one will be tracked, and if you then have one ModelCallCompleted, it will pair with the last started.

